d that under\nthe new tenement house law, pussed\nto mitigate the evils of congestion in\nthe slums, 301,000 rooms ure left in\ntenement houses in tills cflty to which\nneither light nor air eon penetrate.\n\u201cIt luis been found,\u201d lie said, \u201cthat\nplants cannot live in these dens.\nHow can we expect children to grow\nup there? Do you think good cit\nizens can spring from .such homes?\u201d\nlie (inquired. Mr. Riis took excep\ntions to efforts to amend the tene\nment house statutes by Several hills\nnow pending in the Albany leglsla\nturn\n\u201cThe Gilchrist hill,\u201d he said, \u201cwill\npermit bakeries to do business again\nat idight in tenement basements, thus\nexposing lives of families to death\nby fits*. The Strauss bill (icriiiits the\noccupation of unventilated rooms.\u201d\nHe believed these and other bills\nwhich he claimed would add to the\nevils of the congested districts ought\nto bo defeated.\nTHE REOPENING TODAY.\n(Special to The Sentinel.)\nNew York, Mar. 26. \u2014Marking an\nother decided step toward the return\nof prosperity to the metropolis, the\nKnickerbocker Trust company, which\nclosed its doors last October, was re\nopened for business at noon today.\nThe bank has assets of over $50,-\n000,000, with liabilities slightly\nless, and there is every likelihood it\nwill be able to pay all of the 20,000\ndepositors in full.\nThe reopening of the Knicker-\nbooker Trust company, in accordance\nwith plans for Its rehabilitation, pre\npared after four months\u2019 labor by\na committee of depositors, released\nto 'the community assets aggregating\n16.370,020.\n\u201cThe reopening of the Knicker\nbocker Trust company,\u201d declared\nJames Russell Seely of the counsel\nfor the depositors\u2019 committee, \u201cwill\nhave a stimulating effect not only\nupon the local financial situation,\nbut upon every financial center on\nthe globe. It Is the best thing that\nhas happened since the panic.\u201d\nJustice Clarke, in dismissing the\ntemporary receivers of the suspend\ned trust company and signing the re\nsumption order, spoke In '\u2022oramen\n\u2022datory vein of the work of the de\npositors\u2019 committee, counsel and oth\ners who had labored so assiduously\nIn working out the rehabilitation\nplan.\nUnder the terms of this plan the\ndepositors of the Knickerbocker\nTrust company will not receive their\ndeposits In full when the trust com\npany opens its doors, hut will receive\n10 per cent, today if they want it\nand the remaining portions of the\ndeposits can be withdrawn at Inter\nvals covering a period of about two\nand one-half years.\nMayor Speer of Denver has ord\nered that distribution stations for\n2 0,000 shade trees to be given the\ncitizens of Denver and paid for out\nof the city funds, bo established and\nthe distribution made on April 16\nDelights <>r the Sea.\nThe Colorado Southern\u2019s low\nrates and splendid service places the\nMexican Gulf within only a few hours\ndistance. Let us tell you of the\nsplendid attractions.\nT. E. FISHER. G. P. A., Denver.\nPostoitice\nBook Store\nHeadquarters\nFor\nSchool Supplies\nOffice Supplies\nFancy Box Station\nary\nMagazines of all\nhinds\nImported and domestic\ncigars and tobacco\nM. F. FredeiicKs.\nflnWalley&Hall\nj CIVIL AND MINING ENGINEERS.\nLand and Mine Surveying. Irri\ngation Projects Investigated.\nThe Reclamation of Seepage\nLuuh a Specialty.\nPhone Junction 400: Room 108, Sen*\ntlnel Building.\nTack Your Clothes in\nMOTHINE\nThe most effective and convenient\ndestroyer of moths ever invented.\nPrice, 15c a Package.\ncobucw nmi and maim.\nTHURSDAY, MARCH 2\u00ab, 1908.\n\u201cPOOR LITTLE GIRL\u201d\nSAID THE WORLD\nA Miserable Wreck, Chester Gillette Awaits the Coming of\nNext Week When He Must Die for the Murder of\nHis Sweetheart, Grace Brown\u2014The Old, Old\nStory\u2014Pathetic Letters of the Broken\nHearted Girl are Classics.\n(By Glenn Guernsey.)\nNew York, Mar. 2 6.\u2014A pallid,\ncowering youth, led shrinkingly into\nthe room of sudden death by pitying\nbut implacable executioners, strap\nped shuddering, into the fatal elec\ntric chair and then hurled, quickly\nand quietly, into enternity\u2014this is\nto be the fate next week of Chester\nE. Gillette. So will end the last\nchapter in the tragedy of Big Moose\nLake, in which Grace Brown gave\nup her life for love of the cowardly,\nwretched lad whose life must now\npay the penalty of his crime. To the\nlast the famous prisoner of Auburn\npenitentiary maintains his innocence\n\u2014declares that Grace Brown leaped\nfrom the boat on that trip on Big\nMoose Lake which was to have been\ntheir honeymoon voyage, and that,\nhe, frightened, ran away and let li r\ndrown.\nIt is an old story, this tragedy of\nBig Moose Lake\u2014a story of the great\nlove of a maid for a man, an affec\ntion so overpowering that she will\ningly placed her honor and good\nname in his keeping. The man tired\nof his conquest, as men so often do,\nand sought relief from the ties that\nbound him by slaying the innocent\nyoung girl who had loved and trust\ned him with all her heart.\n\u201cPoor little girl!\u201d said the Herki\nmer policeman who found the\nswoolen, battered body of \"one more\nunfortunate,\u201d and \u201cPoor little girl!\u201d\nthe people of the nation echoed\nwhen her letters, written to the man\nwho had so often promised to marry\nher and had so often failed, were\nread during Gillette\u2019s trial in the\nlittle Herkimer court house. Those\nletters, written from a heart waver\ning between love and shame, are\nclassics and might well furnish ma\nterial for a poet, a novelist or a\nphilosopher.\nAfter Gillette had postponed the\nwedding she wrote him:\n\u201cI simply can\u2019t stay here any long\ner. Mamma worries and wonders\nwhy I cry so much. Please come and\ntake me, dear. 1 am afraid you\nwon\u2019t come and. I\u2019m frightened, dear.\nChester, thero is not a girl in the\nwhole world so miserable ns I am\ntonight, and you have made me feel\nso. I don\u2019t mean that, dear; you\nhave always been so good to me and\n1 know you always will be.\u201d\nThree weeks before her death she\nwrote, from the depths of her poor,\nbuffeted heart.\n\u201cI won\u2019t Interfere with any of\nyour plans. I was ill nearly all yes\nterday, and tonight the veins In my l\nhead are frightfully Bwollen. Mam\nina bathed, them in cologne and they\nare not so bad today. They were\nswollen becauso I cry so much.\nChester, I don't suppose you will\never know how I regret being all\nthis trouble to you. 1 know you\n1 hate me and I can\u2019t blame you one\nbit. My whole life is ruined, and\n'ln a measure yours, too. Of course\nI M\u2019s worse for me than you. but the\nworld and you, too, think I am the\none to blame, but somehow 1 can\u2019t\n\u2014just simply can\u2019t think I am,\nChester. I said, \u2018No,\u2019 so many times,\ndear. Of course the world will not\nknow that but it\u2019s true, all the Bamc.\nMy little sister came up just a min\nute ago with her hands full of\ndaisies and asked me if I didn\u2019t want\nmy fortune told. I told her I guess\ned it was pretty well told. Now, I\ndon\u2019t want you to mind this letter,\nfor I am blue tonight.\u201d\nAnd there were many other letters\n\u2014pitiful appeals that would have\ntouched the most hardened heart:\n\u201cI will try and not worry. You\nare a dear, anyhow. I have cried\nso much I am a sight, dear. I am\nso thin, and my face is so deathly\nExcursion to Glenwooc^\nI Via. Colorado Midland m\nI Saturday March 28th\n1 $2.50 Round Trip 1\nj\n(Special Train Leaves Grand Junction at 8: a. m.\nReturning Leaves Glenwood at 11:30 p, m.\nI Bands\u2019 on Train\u2014High School Ball\nGame\u2014W. 0. W. Drills\u2014Swimming\nContest in Pool- \u2019JSJTSttZ\nCl Vickery Gen. Agen^\nwhite.\n\u201cO. I can\u2019t wait until I see you\nagain. We will be happy and I\nwon\u2019t get cross. I know you will be\nawful good, to me, dear, for I will\ndie in a short time. I know I will,\nand then\u2014O. I think you will al\nways be glad you were so good to\nme.\n\u201cIf I had the strength, dear, I be\nlieve 1 should walk to the river and\nthrow myself in. It would be rather\ncowardly and I despise a coward,\nbut I would not be a bother to you\nany longer. O, Chester, the thought j\nthat I am in your way just drives\nine crazy. How l want to die no one!\nbut myself knows. You would\nsmile if you know hpw lam trying;\nto get strong, for I don\u2019t care how\nrough my life Is after next Saturday.\nI think I could carry packs, like wo\nmen peddlers. I shall certainly die\nif you don\u2019t come. Dear, don\u2019t make\nme suffer any after next Saturday,\nplease. 1 just can\u2019t bear it,, and I\ndon\u2019t think I deserve it, do you? I\ndon\u2019t suppose I shall be home for\nsome time, shall I? Maybe not until\nlam sent home dead. You know,\ndear, that you promised me that.\u201d\nFour days before her death Grace\nBrown wrote this letter to Chester\nGillette:\n\u201cI have been bidding goodbye to\nsome places today. There are so\nmany nooks, dear, and all of them\nso dear to me. I have lived here\nI nearly all my life. First I said good\ni bye to the spring house, with Its\ngreat masses of green moss: then\nthe apple tree where we had our\nplay house: then the \u2018bee hive,\u2019 a\ncute little house in the orchard, and\n-of course, all of the neighbors that\nhave mended my dresses from a little\ntot up. to save me from a thrashing\ni I really deserved.\n\"O, dear, you don\u2019t realize what j\nall this Is to me. I know I shall\nnever see any of them again: and\nmamma! great heavens, how I love\nmamma! I don\u2019t know what I shall 1\ndo without her. She is never cross;\nand she always helps me so much, j\nSometimes I think if I could tell\nmamma, but I can\u2019t. She has trou\nble enough as it Is. and I couldn\u2019t\nbreak her heart like that. If I come\nback dead, perhaps if she does know\nshe won\u2019t be angry with me. I will\nnever be happy again, dear, I wish\nI could die. .You will never know\nwhat you have made me suffer, dear.\nI miss you and I want to see you,\nbut I wish I could die.\u201d\n\u201cI wish I could die!\u201d How soon\nI the poor girl had her desire!\nPerhaps it was better so. Perhaps\nthe world, which now finds it so easy\nto forgive and which weeps over the\nmemory of Grace Brown, might have\nbeen hard and adamant if she had\nlived to face her shame.\nYet Grace Brown would have had\none friend\u2014her mother\u2014who de\nclared: \u201cWhile others may condemn\nher, I know that she was sweet and\npure and good, and I feel she has\nproved what a great sacriifee a good\nwoman will make for her love.\u201d\nAnd Chester Gillette Is not yet de\nserted. '1 know that my boy Is\ninnocent.\u201d declares he aged woman\nwho bore him, \"and that God will\nyet save him frAm the fate that\nthreatens.\u201d\nRing Mesa 105 wnen you are In\nieed of a livery rig or a wagon for\nieavy hauling. Barton TerrefT\nlave one of the best eaulpped livery\nind most modern livery barii\u00df In the\ndate. Located at Fifth and Colora\nio. Prices reasonable. Good service\nguaranteed.\nTents and wagon covers.\u2014Fred j\nMantey.\nDo You SIBIpI\nPride in\nWearing\nPretty\nShoes\nMost women do\u2014and this store\nis the home of style and durability\nJohn Kelly and Krippentforf\nDitt man never made us a poor shoe\ndou t they ever wijl.\nFor example, see this new Patent\n.Colt \u201cOrient\u201d tie \u20143 eyelets\u2014wide\nm m We would appreciate a call.\nWe aim to please.\nMcConnell Lowe\nReal Estate Investments\u2014\nHigh Line land from $2O per acre.\n40-acres sandy loam\u2014plowed\u2014under Grand Valley canal. Only\n$112.50 per acre.\n12-acres young orchard northeast of town. $325.00 per acre.\nFull bearing Clifton orchard, $12,000.\nCity residences at reasonable prrlces in good localities.\nCity lots from $3OO to $O5O per pair on Main street.\nRENT COLLECTION!*, \u00abCTC.\nIf you are a non-resident,